# Trust Layer

## Purpose

This section distinguishes operational trust from adjacent but non-identical concepts such as governance, safety, compliance, reliability, and observability.

## Working argument

Trust is not a generic label. In operational environments, trust is earned through repeated credible behavior under defined constraints.

A system becomes trust-bearing when users can rely on it without over-trusting it, constantly compensating for it, or losing clarity about who remains accountable.

## Working definition

Bounded operational trust is the degree to which a system can be relied on within a defined operating scope to surface, qualify, or support action credibly, without generating unmanageable noise, hidden logic, or ambiguous responsibility.

## Distinctions to preserve

- Observability provides visibility.
- Governance defines rules and accountability structures.
- Safety addresses harm prevention and boundary conditions.
- Compliance addresses adherence to standards or requirements.
- Reliability addresses consistent technical functioning.
- Trust concerns whether the system can be used credibly in practice.

